    "body": "I'm trying to rewrite a wrapper from custom C to Cython, and I need to use `ioctl()`.\r\n\r\nIf I use the `posix.ioctl.ioctl()` function, I get an error:\r\n\r\n```\r\nError compiling Cython file:\r\n------------------------------------------------------------\r\n...\r\n\r\n    io_hdr.sbp = sense\r\n    io_hdr.mx_sb_len = len(sense)\r\n    io_hdr.timeout = 1800000\r\n\r\n    result = ioctl(fid.fileno(), SG_IO, &io_hdr)\r\n                                       ^\r\n------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nlinux_sgio/linux_sgio.pyx:135:40: Cannot convert 'sg_io_hdr_t *' to Python object\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe shortened version of the sources would be:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfrom posix.ioctl import ioctl\r\n\r\ndef foo(fid):\r\n    cdef sg_io_hdr_t io_hdr\r\n\r\n    ioctl(fid.fileno(), SG_IO, &io_hdr)\r\n```\r\n",
    "closed_at": "2020-03-24T08:50:12Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "You need to use `cimport`, not `import`. You're currently trying to import a regular Python function, which can't be called since a pointer isn't a Python object. `cimport` loads the C-definitions from a `.pyx`/`.pyd` [file](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/master/Cython/Includes/posix/ioctl.pxd), adding the `#include` to the outputted C file and treating the functions with the appropriate semantics.",
